  # Automation Bridge Requests + Journey Engine
  
  This folder contains both:
  1. **Bruno helper requests** that extract dynamic IDs from B2B messages.
  2. **Node.js journey engine** (`core.js` + `lib/`, `providers/`, `journeys/`,
     `runner/`) that drives end-to-end automation from the CLI runner and
     the FTTH-Mobily-Toolkit web UI.
  
  ## Bruno Helpers â€” Usage Flow
  1. Create an order (TMF622) â†’ orderId is auto-captured
  2. Wait ~60-90 seconds for system processing
  3. Run "Extract Integration IDs" to fetch serviceOrderId + svActionId
  4. Continue with TMF641 notifications, WFM steps, and SingleView calls
  
  ## Variables Set
  - `serviceOrderId` â†’ Used in TMF641 notification body (serviceOrder.id)
  - `svActionId` â†’ Used in SingleView 622 notifications (salesOrder.externalId)
  - `workOrderIdCpe` â†’ Auto-generated if not set (WFM CPE Step-01)
  - `workOrderIdMe` â†’ Auto-generated if not set (WFM ME Step-01)
  
  ## Journey Engine Module Layout (SOLID)
  
  `core.js` is now a thin facade that re-exports from focused modules:
  
  - `lib/runtime.js`         â€” init / log / delay / cancellation
  - `lib/env-bru.js`         â€” parse `environments/*.bru` and Bruno files
  - `lib/json-utils.js`      â€” `subVars`, `cleanJsonBody`, deep-find
  - `lib/url-builder.js`     â€” portal API URL builders
  - `lib/http.js`            â€” `httpRequest`, `runBruRequest` + audit logs
  - `lib/auth.js`            â€” OAuth per environment
  - `lib/b2b.js`             â€” B2B message helpers (action matching, payload parsing)
  - `lib/state.js`           â€” order state extraction + `doWaitForOrderState`
  - `lib/extractors.js`      â€” polling-based ID extractors
  - `lib/notifications.js`   â€” `doNotification`, `doCreateOrder`, SV trigger
  - `lib/tasks.js`           â€” Telflow task list/complete
  
  - `providers/network-category.js` â€” FTTH CONSUMER vs FTTH RCY routing
  - `providers/mobily.js`           â€” Mobily activation + field-work builders
  - `providers/openaccess.js`       â€” OA notifications, ID specs, OA builder
  
  - `journeys/builders.js`   â€” generic journey patterns (simple, suspend, â€¦)
  - `journeys/labels.js`     â€” step labels + state maps + failure code lists
  - `journeys/registry.js`   â€” `JOURNEY_REGISTRY` (every provider Ã— type)
  
  - `runner/state-detector.js`  â€” `detectOrderPosition`
  - `runner/extract-all-ids.js` â€” toolkit one-shot ID snapshot
  - `runner/resume.js`          â€” resume-from logic
  - `runner/step-executor.js`   â€” `step.type` dispatcher (with externalId log)
  - `runner/runner.js`          â€” top-level `runJourney`
  
  ## ODB Patch Routing (Phase 4B)
  
  The runner picks ODB-patch behaviour from `networkCategory` (not customer
  type as before):
  
    FTTH CONSUMER â†’ ODB patch is required (Regular customers)
    FTTH RCY      â†’ ODB patch is skipped  (Royal customers)
  
  See `providers/network-category.js`. The Mobily activation builder also
  injects `customerCategory` + `networkCategory` into `vars` on the create
  step so the TMF622 payload always carries the Phase 4B characteristics
  regardless of what's in the env file.
}


